{"ts": "2026-06-07T21:25:47.389949+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "Now I have a full understanding of the issue. Let me take action. I'll add a comment acknowledging the bug and apply the \"bug\" label.", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 2451, "prompt_tokens": 10088, "total_tokens": 12539, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": null, "reasoning_tokens": 1683, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": null, "cached_tokens": 9984}, "prompt_cache_hit_tokens": 9984, "prompt_cache_miss_tokens": 104}, "model_provider": "openai", "model_name": "deepseek-v4-flash", "system_fingerprint": "fp_8b330d02d0_prod0820_fp8_kvcache_20260402", "id": "7ca4135e-0a28-4c4d-85ea-52b0893c3df3", "finish_reason": "tool_calls", "logprobs": null}, "type": "ai", "name": null, "id": "lc_run--019ea3f9-e036-7a53-9c5b-9ab80d82ae2d-0", "tool_calls": [{"name": "issue_write", "args": {"owner": "rpnr-bench", "repo": "T11_R01_C03_A03", "issue_number": 1, "method": "update", "labels": ["bug"], "title": "apply_migrations.sh applies files in wrong order on filesystems with case-folding"}, "id": "call_00_6vH7AMGGAnDmbONY4chB4725", "type": "tool_call"}, {"name": "add_issue_comment", "args": {"owner": "rpnr-bench", "repo": "T11_R01_C03_A03", "issue_number": 1, "body": "## Triage\n\nThank you for the detailed report and the additional data point on Linux. Confirmed as a legitimate bug.\n\n### Root cause\n\nThe script `scripts/apply_migrations.sh` uses a bare shell glob loop:\n\n```bash\nfor f in migrations/*.sql; do\n```\n\nShell glob expansion is sorted according to the current locale's collation rules (`LC_COLLATE`). On case-insensitive filesystems (APFS) or with certain locales (C.UTF-8), the resulting order can differ from the numeric prefix order (`001_`, `002_`, `003_`), causing migration files to be applied out of sequence. Since `002_create_sessions.sql` has a foreign key into `users` (from `001_`) and `003_add_session_index.sql` indexes a column on `sessions` (from `002_`), incorrect ordering leads to the errors described.\n\n### Migration dependency chain\n\n```\n001_create_users.sql      → creates users table\n002_create_sessions.sql   → creates sessions (FK → users)\n003_add_session_index.sql → creates index on sessions(user_id)\n```\n\n### Suggested fix\n\nThe most robust approach is to sort the file list explicitly with `LC_ALL=C` to guarantee byte-wise ordering regardless of the user's locale. For example:\n\n```bash\nfor f in $(find migrations/ -maxdepth 1 -name '*.sql' | LC_ALL=C sort); do\n    echo \"Applying $f\"\n    docker exec -i \"$CONTAINER\" psql -U \"$DB_USER\" -d \"$DB_NAME\" < \"$f\"\ndone\n```\n\nAlternatively, setting `LC_COLLATE=C` before the glob also works and is slightly simpler:\n\n```bash\n# Force deterministic byte-wise glob ordering\nfor f in migrations/*.sql; do\n    echo \"Applying $f\"\n    docker exec -i \"$CONTAINER\" psql -U \"$DB_USER\" -d \"$DB_NAME\" < \"$f\"\ndone\n``` (just add `export LC_COLLATE=C` beforehand)\n\n@BruceKZ — a PR with either fix would be very welcome. I've added the **bug** label to track this.\n\n### Verification\n\nAfter the fix, running `./scripts/apply_migrations.sh` on a fresh checkout should reliably apply files in `001 → 002 → 003` order on any system."}, "id": "call_01_novnuqXKFKrWG8e5srFc4154", "type": "tool_call"}], "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 10088, "output_tokens": 2451, "total_tokens": 12539, "input_token_details": {"cache_read": 9984}, "output_token_details": {"reasoning": 1683}}}}]}}}
